A first-year doctoral student in education research keeps confusing themselves when reading papers that use regression analysis — they cannot quickly tell whether the paper is doing simple multiple regression, multilevel models, hierarchical linear modeling, fixed effects estimators in panel data methods, or a mixed methods research design with a regression component. They want a casual study tool to build fluency by working through real published abstracts and methods sections. Build a playful study companion app where the student pastes in an abstract or a paragraph from a methods section, and the app walks them through identifying the study's research question, the unit of analysis, the structure of the data (cross-sectional, longitudinal panel, nested students within classrooms within schools), and from those, the appropriate model family. The app should explain why a study with students nested in classrooms requires multilevel models or hierarchical linear modeling rather than treating observations as independent, why a study tracking the same individuals over time often uses fixed effects estimators within panel data methods, when random effects models are preferred and when they are not, and what role interaction terms play when the paper claims that an effect differs across subgroups. The student should be able to log papers they have worked through and tag each with the method, the substantive education research question, and any model diagnostics the authors reported (or skipped). Over weeks the app should track which method families the student is confidently spotting and which still trip them up, serving more practice in weak areas. The point is not to make the student run a regression but to develop the methodological literacy to read the literature critically.